        estimatedMinutes: 20,
        summary: "Anatomical layers of skin, normal histology, functions of epidermis and dermis, and basic understanding of dermatological lesions.",
        contentMd: "# Skin Structure and Lesion Morphology\n\n## Anatomical Layers of Skin\n\n### Epidermis (Ectoderm-derived)\nThickness: 0.05-1.5 mm\n\n#### Five Layers (basal to superficial)\n1. Stratum Basale: Single layer of cuboidal cells, contains melanocytes and Merkel cells\n2. Stratum Spinosum: Multiple layers, desmosomes connect cells (\"spiny\" appearance)\n3. Stratum Granulosum: 2-4 layers, keratohyalin granules visible\n4. Stratum Lucidum: Translucent layer in thick skin (palms, soles)\n5. Stratum Corneum: Dead keratinized cells, continuously shed\n\n### Dermis (Mesoderm-derived)\nThickness: 2-4 mm, divided into two zones\n\n#### Papillary Dermis\n- Loose connective tissue\n- Dermal papillae interdigitate with epidermis\n- Contains: Capillaries, nerve endings, lymphatics\n\n#### Reticular Dermis\n- Dense fibrous tissue\n- Collagen and elastic fibers provide strength\n- Contains: Hair follicles, sweat glands, sebaceous glands\n\n### Subcutaneous Tissue (Hypodermis)\n- Loose connective tissue with fat cells\n- Provides insulation and cushioning\n- Contains larger blood vessels and nerves\n\n## Skin Functions\n1. Barrier: Protection from environment and microbes\n2. Thermoregulation: Sweating and vasodilatation\n3. Sensation: Touch, temperature, pain\n4. Vitamin D synthesis: 7-dehydrocholesterol conversion\n5. Immune function: Langerhan cells and lymphocytes\n6. Water balance: Prevents transepidermal water loss\n\n## Cell Types in Skin\n- Keratinocytes: 95% of epidermis\n- Melanocytes: Pigment production, 1 per 10 keratinocytes\n- Langerhan cells: Antigen presenting cells\n- Merkel cells: Mechanoreceptors\n- Fibroblasts: Collagen and elastic fiber production",
