        slug: "skin-lesion-morphology",
        title: "Skin Structure & Lesion Morphology - Mechanism",
        estimatedMinutes: 25,
        summary: "Detailed classification of primary and secondary skin lesions, morphological descriptions, and histopathological correlations.",
        contentMd: "# Lesion Morphology: Classification and Mechanisms\n\n## Primary Lesions\n\n### Flat Lesions (Non-palpable)\n1. Macule: <1 cm, circumscribed, non-palpable (freckle, vitiligo patch)\n2. Patch: >1 cm, non-palpable area of altered pigmentation\n3. Erythema: Red coloration from increased blood flow\n4. Ecchymosis: Black-blue discoloration from bleeding\n\n### Raised Lesions (Palpable)\n1. Papule: <1 cm, solid elevation (acne, lichen planus)\n2. Nodule: >1 cm, deeper lesion in dermis or subcutaneous tissue\n3. Plaque: >1 cm, confluent papules with flat top (psoriasis)\n4. Vesicle: <1 cm, fluid-filled blister (chickenpox)\n5. Bulla: >1 cm, fluid-filled blister (pemphigus)\n6. Pustule: Vesicle filled with pus (acne)\n7. Wheal: Transient, edematous papule/plaque (urticaria)\n8. Tumor: Large mass (lipoma, cyst)\n\n### Linear Lesions\n1. Petechiae: Pinpoint red macules from capillary bleeding\n2. Purpura: Bleeding into skin (palpable vs non-palpable)\n3. Streak: Linear arrangement (Koebner phenomenon)\n\n## Secondary Lesions (changes to primary lesions)\n\n### Loss of Epidermis\n1. Erosion: Partial epidermal loss, heals without scar\n2. Ulcer: Full dermal loss, heals with scar\n3. Excoriation: Traumatic removal of epidermis\n\n### Accumulation of Epidermis\n1. Scale: Excess stratum corneum (psoriasis, eczema)\n2. Crust: Dried plasma/blood on skin (eczema, impetigo)\n3. Lichenification: Thickened skin with exaggerated markings\n\n### Changes in Pigmentation\n1. Hyperpigmentation: Increased melanin (melasma)\n2. Hypopigmentation: Decreased melanin (vitiligo)\n3. Depigmentation: Complete loss (albinism)\n\n## Morphological Descriptors\n\n### Distribution Patterns\n- Localized: Single site\n- Regional: Specific area (face, extensor surfaces)\n- Generalized: Entire body\n- Symmetric: Both sides equally affected\n- Asymmetric: One side only\n- Linear: Along Blaschko's lines or dermatomes\n\n### Arrangement\n- Scattered: Random distribution\n- Grouped: Clustered together\n- Confluent: Coalesced into larger area\n- Annular: Ring-shaped\n- Arciform: Arc-shaped\n- Serpiginous: Snake-like borders\n\n## Histopathological Correlations\n\n### Intraepidermal Lesions\n- Vesicle: Acantholysis (pemphigus) or spongiosis (eczema)\n- Mechanism: Separation of epidermal cells\n\n### Subepidermal Lesions\n- Bulla: Separation at dermal-epidermal junction\n- Pemphigoid: Antibodies against basement membrane\n\n### Dermal Involvement\n- Nodule: Infiltrate of cells in dermis/subcutaneous tissue\n- Inflammation: Vasculitis, granuloma, or lymphocytic infiltration\n\n## Palpation and Assessment\n\n### Texture\n- Smooth: Normal skin\n- Rough: Scaling, lichenification\n- Indurated: Hardened, thickened\n- Fluctuant: Fluid within (cyst, abscess)\n\n### Temperature\n- Warm: Inflammation, infection\n- Cold: Ischemia, poor perfusion\n\n### Consistency\n- Firm: Normal skin, scar\n- Soft: Edema, fat\n- Rubbery: Cyst, lipoma",
