        title: "Skin Structure & Lesion Morphology - Clinical Context",
        estimatedMinutes: 25,
        summary: "Clinical assessment of skin lesions, differential diagnosis based on morphology, systemic disease associations, and diagnostic techniques.",
        contentMd: "# Clinical Assessment of Skin and Lesions\n\n## Systematic Skin Examination\n\n### Complete Examination Protocol\n1. Inspect entire skin (include scalp, palms, soles, genitals, nails)\n2. Palpate lesions (texture, temperature, tenderness)\n3. Assess distribution and pattern\n4. Look for systemic signs (lymphadenopathy, hepatomegaly)\n5. Document size, shape, color, arrangement\n6. Photograph for records (with patient consent)\n\n## Morphology-Based Differential Diagnosis\n\n### Vesicular Lesions\n1. Viral (Varicella, HSV, VZV): Grouped, painful, dermatomal\n2. Bullous pemphigoid: Tense bullae on flexures\n3. Pemphigus vulgaris: Flaccid bullae, oral involvement\n4. Dyshidrotic eczema: Pruritic, palmar/plantar distribution\n\n### Papulosquamous Lesions\n1. Psoriasis: Symmetric, extensor surfaces, silvery scale\n2. Lichen planus: Violaceous, wickham's striae, mucosal involvement\n3. Pityriasis rosea: Herald patch, Christmas tree distribution\n4. Seborrheic keratosis: Greasy scale, \"stuck on\" appearance\n\n### Erythematous Macules/Patches\n1. Measles: Prodrome, cough, coryza, Koplik spots\n2. Scarlet fever: Sandpaper texture, strawberry tongue\n3. Rubella: Maculopapular, posterior cervical lymphadenopathy\n4. Meningococcemia: Non-blanching petechiae, systemic toxicity\n\n### Nodules and Masses\n1. Lipoma: Soft, mobile, subcutaneous\n2. Cyst: Fluctuant, fluid-filled\n3. Melanoma: Asymmetry, border irregularity, color variation (ABCDE)\n4. Basal cell carcinoma: Pearly nodule with telangiectasia\n5. Squamous cell carcinoma: Ulcerated, scaling nodule\n\n## Diagnostic Techniques\n\n### Non-Invasive Methods\n1. Wood's lamp: Fungal infections (coral red - tinea versicolor), vitiligo (enhanced)\n2. KOH mount: Fungal hyphae and spores\n3. Gram stain: Bacterial identification\n4. Diascopy: Vasculitis (non-blanching petechiae), sarcoidosis\n\n### Invasive Methods\n1. Skin biopsy: Punch, shave, or excisional\n2. Culture: Bacterial, fungal, viral\n3. Electron microscopy: Viral structures\n4. Immunofluorescence: Autoimmune blistering diseases\n\n## Systemic Disease Manifestations in Skin\n\n### Connective Tissue Diseases\n1. Lupus: Malar rash, photosensitivity, discoid lesions\n2. Scleroderma: Skin thickening, Raynaud's phenomenon\n3. Dermatomyositis: Heliotrope rash, Gottron papules\n\n### Infectious Diseases\n1. Syphilis: Macules, papules, gummas (stages)\n2. Leprosy: Hypoesthetic macules, nerve thickening\n3. TB: Scrofuloderma, lupus vulgaris\n\n### Endocrine Disorders\n1. Diabetes: Necrobiosis lipoidica, diabetic blisters\n2. Thyroid: Myxedema, exophthalmos\n3. Adrenal: Hyperpigmentation (Addison's disease)\n\n## Lesion Assessment in Indian Practice\n\n### Common Environmental Factors\n1. Sun exposure: Photoaging, solar elastosis\n2. Tropical climate: Increased fungal/viral infections\n3. Pollution: Acne aggravation, pigmentary changes\n4. Occupational: Dermatitis, occupational cancers\n\n### Diagnostic Priorities in Resource-Limited Settings\n1. Clinical diagnosis based on morphology\n2. Simple staining techniques (KOH, Gram)\n3. Selective biopsying for unclear cases\n4. Photo documentation for follow-up",
