        title: "Eczema & Contact Dermatitis - Foundation",
        estimatedMinutes: 20,
        summary: "Overview of eczema pathophysiology, types of dermatitis, clinical presentation patterns, and epidemiology of inflammatory skin conditions.",
        contentMd: "# Eczema and Contact Dermatitis\n\n## Definitions\n\n### Eczema (Dermatitis)\nInflammatory condition with pruritus, erythema, edema, and possible vesiculation. Acute or chronic.\n\n### Contact Dermatitis\nInflammatory reaction of skin to external agent. Irritant (non-immunologic) or Allergic (immunologic).\n\n## Types of Eczema\n\n### Atopic Dermatitis (Atopic Eczema)\n- Chronic, relapsing inflammatory condition\n- Associated with atopy (asthma, rhinitis, allergies)\n- 10-20% prevalence in children, 1-3% in adults\n- Impaired skin barrier and immune dysregulation\n\n### Contact Dermatitis\n1. Irritant: 80% of contact dermatitis, non-allergic\n2. Allergic: 20%, type IV hypersensitivity\n\n### Other Types\n- Seborrheic dermatitis: Malassezia overgrowth\n- Nummular eczema: Coin-shaped lesions\n- Varicose eczema: Over varicose veins\n- Discoid eczema: Discoid pattern similar to nummular\n\n## Pathophysiology Overview\n\n### Atopic Dermatitis\n1. Filaggrin gene mutations (FLG) - 30% of cases\n2. Impaired barrier function\n3. Increased TEWL (transepidermal water loss)\n4. Th2-mediated immune response\n5. IgE elevation and eosinophilia\n\n### Contact Dermatitis\n- Irritant: Direct cytotoxic effect\n- Allergic: Hapten-carrier complex, sensitization phase, elicitation phase\n\n## Clinical Features Common to Both\n\n### Acute Phase\n- Erythema and edema\n- Vesicles and blisters\n- Intense pruritus (worse at night)\n- Burning sensation\n- Exudation in severe cases\n\n### Chronic Phase\n- Lichenification (thickened skin)\n- Hyperpigmentation or hypopigmentation\n- Excoriations from scratching\n- Secondary bacterial infection\n\n## Distribution Patterns\n\n### Atopic Dermatitis\n- Face, neck, hands, feet, flexures\n- Typically symmetric\n- Spares palms and soles (usually)\n\n### Contact Dermatitis\n- Depends on allergen/irritant exposure\n- Well-demarcated borders following contact area\n- May be linear or patterned\n\n## Indian Context\n- High prevalence due to tropical climate, dust, pollution\n- Allergic contact dermatitis common (bindi, cosmetics, nickel jewelry)\n- Occupational dermatitis in agricultural and industrial workers\n- Secondary infection high due to heat, humidity, poor hygiene",
        mnemonics: [
          { text: "AD Itch", explanation: "Atopic Dermatitis - chronic, relapsing, intensely itchy" },
          { text: "Contact: 80-20", explanation: "80% irritant, 20% allergic contact dermatitis" }
        ],
