        title: "Eczema & Contact Dermatitis - Mechanism",
        estimatedMinutes: 25,
        summary: "Detailed pathophysiological mechanisms, immunological pathways, barrier dysfunction, and inflammatory cascade in eczematous diseases.",
        contentMd: "# Eczema & Contact Dermatitis: Pathophysiology\n\n## Atopic Dermatitis Mechanisms\n\n### Barrier Defects\n1. Filaggrin (FLG) mutations: 30% of moderate-severe AD\n   - Reduced filaggrin protein\n   - Impaired stratum corneum formation\n   - Increased transepidermal water loss (TEWL)\n\n2. Lipid abnormalities:\n   - Reduced ceramides (lipid layer)\n   - Altered fatty acids\n   - Impaired barrier sealing\n\n3. Tight junction defects:\n   - Claudin-1 mutations\n   - Zonula occludens (ZO-1) dysfunction\n\n### Immune Dysregulation\n\n#### Early Phase\n1. Th2 predominance (IL-4, IL-5, IL-13)\n2. IgE elevation\n3. Eosinophilia\n\n#### Late Phase\n1. Th1 response (IFN-gamma)\n2. Chronic inflammation\n3. IL-17 involvement (intrinsic AD)\n\n### Pruritus Pathways\n1. Increased nerve fiber density (TRPV1, TRPA1)\n2. Neuropeptide overexpression (substance P)\n3. Reduced pain threshold\n4. Central sensitization\n\n## Contact Dermatitis Mechanisms\n\n### Irritant Contact Dermatitis\n1. Barrier disruption by irritant\n2. Cytokine release (TNF-alpha, IL-1)\n3. Non-specific immune activation\n4. Proportional to irritant concentration and exposure time\n5. No sensitization required\n\n### Allergic Contact Dermatitis\n\n#### Sensitization Phase (Induction)\n1. Hapten penetration through barrier\n2. Hapten-protein binding\n3. Langerhans cell uptake and presentation\n4. Th1 and Tc cell priming\n5. Migration to draining lymph nodes\n6. Clonal expansion (5-7 days minimum)\n\n#### Elicitation Phase (Challenge)\n1. Re-exposure to allergen\n2. Hapten-specific T cell recognition\n3. Cytokine release (TNF-alpha, IFN-gamma)\n4. Increased vascular permeability\n5. Erythema and edema within 24-72 hours\n\n## Histopathology\n\n### Acute Phase\n1. Spongiosis: Intercellular edema\n2. Vesicle formation from fluid accumulation\n3. Lymphocytic infiltration (dermis)\n4. Edema of papillary dermis\n\n### Chronic Phase\n1. Lichenification: Acanthosis (epidermal thickening)\n2. Parakeratosis: Retained nuclei in corneum\n3. Fibrosis of dermis\n4. Decreased granular layer\n\n## Scratch Cycle\n1. Pruritus triggers scratching\n2. Trauma damages barrier\n3. Barrier disruption increases TEWL\n4. Dry skin increases pruritus\n5. Positive feedback loop\n\n## Inflammatory Cascade\n\n### Key Mediators\n1. Cytokines: IL-4, IL-5, IL-13 (Th2)\n2. Chemokines: CCL17, CCL22 (recruit T cells)\n3. Neuropeptides: Substance P, CGRP\n4. Proteases: Kallikrein-7 (barrier disruption)\n\n## Secondary Infection Mechanisms\n1. Impaired skin barrier\n2. Scratching creates portals of entry\n3. Impaired innate immunity\n4. Staphylococcus aureus colonization\n5. S. aureus toxins (Panton-Valentine leukocidin) worsen inflammation",
