        estimatedMinutes: 20,
        summary: "Overview of urticaria types, pathophysiology, drug-induced reactions, classification systems, and epidemiology.",
        contentMd: "# Urticaria and Drug Reactions\n\n## Urticaria Definition\nTransient edematous reaction manifesting as wheals (hives) with intense pruritus, typically lasting <24 hours per lesion.\n\n## Classification of Urticaria\n\n### Acute Urticaria\n- Duration: <6 weeks\n- Often identifiable cause\n- Common allergens: Foods, drugs, insect stings, infections\n- Better prognosis than chronic\n\n### Chronic Urticaria\n- Duration: >6 weeks\n- Often idiopathic (50%)\n- Autoimmune (35-40%)\n- Less responsive to standard treatment\n\n### Physical Urticarias\n1. Dermographism: Mechanical trauma\n2. Delayed pressure urticaria: Pressure application\n3. Cold urticaria: Cold exposure\n4. Heat urticaria: Thermal stimulus\n5. Solar urticaria: UV exposure\n6. Aquagenic urticaria: Water contact (rare)\n7. Cholinergic urticaria: Exercise, heat, emotional stress\n\n## Drug-Induced Reactions Classification\n\n### Type I (IgE-mediated, Anaphylactic)\n- Onset: Minutes to 2 hours\n- Common drugs: Penicillins, cephalosporins, NSAIDs\n- Features: Urticaria, angioedema, anaphylaxis\n\n### Type II (Cytotoxic, Antibody-mediated)\n- Hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenia\n- Common drugs: Quinidine, phenacetin\n- Rare manifestation in skin\n\n### Type III (Immune Complex, Serum Sickness)\n- Onset: 7-14 days\n- Features: Urticaria, arthralgia, lymphadenopathy, fever\n- Common drugs: Antibiotics, anticonvulsants\n\n### Type IV (Delayed, Cell-mediated)\n- Onset: 24-72 hours or later\n- Features: Contact dermatitis, exanthems\n- Common drugs: Antibiotics, NSAIDs\n\n### Type V (Stimulatory/Functional)\n- Direct mast cell activation\n- Drugs: Codeine, vancomycin, NSAIDs\n\n## Pathophysiology Overview\n\n### Mast Cell Activation\n1. Allergen-IgE binding → degranulation\n2. Direct chemical activation\n3. Complement activation (C3a, C5a)\n\n### Mediators Released\n1. Histamine: Vasodilation, pruritus\n2. Tryptase: Inflammation\n3. Prostaglandins: Vasodilation, inflammation\n4. Leukotrienes: Vasodilation, inflammation\n\n### Wheal Formation\n1. Mast cell degranulation\n2. Histamine release\n3. Capillary vasodilation\n4. Increased vascular permeability\n5. Local edema (dermis and subcutis)\n\n## Clinical Features\n\n### Characteristic Presentation\n1. Erythematous wheals with pale central edema\n2. Central pallor surrounded by erythematous flare\n3. Well-demarcated lesions\n4. Pruritus (often intense)\n5. Individual lesions resolve in <24 hours\n6. No residual scarring\n\n### Angioedema\n- Deeper dermal/subcutaneous edema\n- Occurs with or without urticaria\n- Involves face, lips, tongue, throat\n- Risk of airway compromise\n\n## Common Triggers in India\n1. Foods: Shellfish, peanuts, tree nuts, eggs, milk\n2. Medications: Antibiotics, NSAIDs, anticonvulsants\n3. Infections: Bacterial UTIs, viral infections\n4. Insect stings/bites\n5. Environmental: Pollen, dust mites\n6. Physical factors: Sunlight, heat, pressure",
