        summary: "Clinical diagnosis, trigger identification, investigation protocols, and management strategies for acute and chronic urticaria.",
        contentMd: "# Clinical Management of Urticaria and Drug Reactions\n\n## Diagnostic Approach\n\n### History Taking\n1. Onset and duration: Acute vs chronic\n2. Associated symptoms: Angioedema, breathing difficulty\n3. Trigger identification:\n   - Food history\n   - Recent medications\n   - Recent infections\n   - Environmental exposures\n   - Physical factors (temperature, pressure)\n4. Pattern: Time of day, specific triggers\n5. Systemic symptoms: Fever, joint pain, lymphadenopathy\n\n### Clinical Examination\n1. Describe wheals: Size, distribution, pattern\n2. Check for dermographism: Draw line on skin\n3. Examine for angioedema\n4. Look for signs of infection\n5. General examination: Lymph nodes, organomegaly\n\n## Investigations\n\n### Routine (All Cases)\n1. Complete blood count: Eosinophilia (allergy), WBC (infection)\n2. Erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR): Elevated in systemic disease\n3. Thyroid function: TSH, antibodies (common association)\n4. Liver function: Baseline\n\n### Selective (Based on History)\n1. Allergy testing:\n   - Prick tests: IgE-mediated food/aeroallergens\n   - Serum specific IgE: Alternative to prick tests\n   - Oral challenge: Gold standard for food allergy\n\n2. Infection screening:\n   - Thyroid antibodies: TPO, TSH receptor\n   - Helicobacter pylori: Common infection association\n   - Viral serology: Hepatitis C (cryoglobulinemia)\n   - Stool for parasites: If indicated\n\n3. Specialized tests:\n   - Basophil activation test (BAT): Autoimmune urticaria\n   - Autologous serum skin test (ASST): Autoimmune markers\n   - Cryoglobulin testing: If cold urticaria\n\n4. Physical urticaria testing:\n   - Ice cube test: 5 min on forearm (cold urticaria)\n   - Dermographism provocation: Firm stroking\n   - Pressure test: 5 lbs weight for 15 min\n\n## Management of Acute Urticaria\n\n### First-Line: Trigger Avoidance\n1. Identify and remove offending agent\n2. Drug discontinuation if medication-induced\n3. Food elimination if food-related\n\n### Pharmacological Treatment\n1. Antihistamines (H1 blockers):\n   - Second-generation (non-sedating preferred): Cetirizine, loratadine\n   - Standard dose for acute\n   - Onset: 30 minutes to 1 hour\n\n2. Topical therapy:\n   - Calamine lotion\n   - Topical corticosteroids (minimal benefit)\n\n3. Systemic corticosteroids:\n   - Only if severe and widespread\n   - Short duration (3-7 days)\n   - Taper to avoid rebound\n\n### Severe/Anaphylaxis\n1. Epinephrine (subcutaneous 0.3-0.5 mg of 1:1000)\n2. Oxygen and airway management\n3. IV antihistamines\n4. IV corticosteroids\n\n## Management of Chronic Urticaria\n\n### Step-Wise Approach\n\n#### Step 1: Second-Generation Antihistamines\n1. Cetirizine 10 mg OD (or BD if severe)\n2. Loratadine 10 mg OD\n3. Fexofenadine 180 mg OD\n4. Response in 70-80% of cases\n\n#### Step 2 (If Step 1 Fails)\n1. Increase antihistamine dose (up to 4x standard)\n2. Consider sedating antihistamine at night (hydroxyzine)\n3. Omalizumab: Anti-IgE monoclonal antibody\n   - Indicated if high IgE\n   - Response rate: 50-80%\n\n#### Step 3 (Refractory Cases)\n1. Cyclosporine\n2. Mycophenolate mofetil\n3. Omalizumab (if not yet tried)\n4. Corticosteroid-sparing agents\n\n### Adjunctive Measures\n1. Avoid triggers: NSAIDs, aspirin, opioids\n2. Temperature control\n3. Stress management\n4. Sleep hygiene\n\n## Management of Physical Urticarias\n\n### Dermographism\n- Antihistamines\n- Avoid trauma\n- Reassurance (usually benign)\n\n### Cholinergic Urticaria\n- Avoid triggers: Heat, exercise, stress\n- Antihistamines (may not be effective)\n- Atropine or anticholinergics (rare)\n\n### Cold Urticaria\n- Avoid cold exposure\n- Antihistamines\n- Gradual cold acclimation\n- Risk of anaphylaxis with systemic cold exposure\n\n## Drug Reaction Management\n\n### Type I (Immediate)\n1. Discontinue offending drug\n2. Epinephrine if anaphylaxis\n3. Antihistamines and corticosteroids\n4. Maintain airway, oxygen, IV access\n\n### Type III (Serum Sickness)\n1. Discontinue offending drug\n2. Systemic corticosteroids (1-2 weeks)\n3. NSAIDs for arthralgia\n4. Antihistamines for urticaria\n\n### Type IV (Delayed-Type)\n1. Drug discontinuation\n2. Topical or systemic corticosteroids\n3. Antihistamines for pruritus\n\n## Prognosis\n- Acute urticaria: 50% resolve within 24 hours\n- Chronic idiopathic: May persist for years (50% resolve within 1 year)\n- Physical urticarias: Often lifelong but manageable",
