        summary: "Key examination points: classification, pathophysiology, investigations, management algorithms, and important clinical distinctions.",
        contentMd: "# Urticaria & Drug Reactions: Examination Focus\n\n## Classification Recall\n\n### Duration-Based\n- Acute: <6 weeks\n- Chronic: >6 weeks\n\n### Etiology-Based\n- Allergic: IgE-mediated\n- Idiopathic: No identifiable cause (50% of chronic)\n- Autoimmune: Autoantibodies (35-40% of chronic)\n- Physical: Thermal, mechanical, chemical stimuli\n\n### Physical Urticaria Types\n1. Dermographism: Most common physical urticaria\n2. Cholinergic: Exercise-induced, \"pinpoint\" wheals\n3. Cold: Ice exposure\n4. Delayed pressure: Pressure 4-6 hours later\n5. Heat: Thermal stimulus\n6. Solar: UV exposure\n7. Aquagenic: Water contact (rare)\n\n## Pathophysiology Summary\n\n### Mast Cell Activation\n- IgE-mediated: Allergen cross-links IgE on FcεRI\n- Non-IgE: Direct chemical activation (NSAIDs, vancomycin)\n- Complement: C3a, C5a anaphylatoxins\n\n### Key Mediators\n- Preformed: Histamine, tryptase, heparin\n- Newly synthesized: Leukotrienes, prostaglandins, cytokines\n\n### Wheal Formation\n- Histamine release → H1 receptor activation\n- Increased capillary permeability\n- Plasma extravasation → dermal edema\n- Flare: Axon reflex and histamine diffusion\n\n## Drug Reaction Classifications\n\n### Type I (Immediate)\n- Onset: Minutes to 2 hours\n- Mechanism: IgE-mediated\n- Features: Urticaria, angioedema, anaphylaxis\n- Common drugs: Penicillins, cephalosporins, NSAIDs\n\n### Type III (Serum Sickness)\n- Onset: 7-14 days\n- Mechanism: Immune complexes + complement\n- Features: Urticaria, arthralgia, fever, lymphadenopathy\n- Common drugs: Antibiotics, anticonvulsants\n\n### Type IV (Delayed-Type)\n- Onset: 24-72 hours or later\n- Mechanism: T cell-mediated\n- Features: Exanthem, contact dermatitis\n- Common drugs: Antibiotics, NSAIDs\n\n## Investigations Quick Reference\n\n### Always Order\n1. CBC: Eosinophilia, infection signs\n2. ESR: Systemic disease\n3. Thyroid function: TSH, TPO antibodies (common)\n4. LFTs: Baseline\n\n### Selective\n1. Allergy testing: Prick test, specific IgE\n2. Infection screening: H. pylori, viral serology\n3. Basophil activation test: Autoimmune urticaria\n4. Skin tests: Ice, dermographism, pressure\n\n## Management Algorithms\n\n### Acute Urticaria\n1. Identify and remove trigger\n2. Antihistamine: Cetirizine 10 mg OD\n3. Short course corticosteroid if severe\n4. Epinephrine if anaphylaxis\n\n### Chronic Urticaria\n\n#### Step 1\n- Second-generation antihistamine OD\n\n#### Step 2 (Failure)\n- Increase antihistamine to 2-4x dose\n- Add omalizumab or cyclosporine\n\n#### Step 3 (Refractory)\n- Cyclosporine or mycophenolate\n- Omalizumab (if not used)\n\n## Exam-Pattern Questions\n\n### Wheal Characteristics\n- Size: Variable, individual lesions\n- Shape: Round to irregular\n- Color: Central pallor, erythematous flare\n- Duration: <24 hours per lesion\n- Distribution: Variable per trigger\n\n### Dermographism Test\n- Procedure: Firm stroking of skin\n- Positive: Wheal appears within 3-5 minutes\n- Most common physical urticaria\n\n### Cold Urticaria Test\n- Ice cube on forearm for 5 minutes\n- Wheal development indicates positive\n- Risk: Systemic anaphylaxis with large cold exposure\n\n### Pressure Urticaria Test\n- Apply 5 lbs weight for 15 minutes\n- Delayed: Wheal appears 4-6 hours later\n- Duration: 8-72 hours\n\n## Important Medications\n\n### Antihistamines\n- First-generation: Sedating (hydroxyzine, chlorpheniramine)\n- Second-generation: Non-sedating (cetirizine, loratadine, fexofenadine)\n\n### Biologic Agents\n- Omalizumab: Anti-IgE, response 50-80%\n- Cyclosporine: Immunosuppressant\n- Mycophenolate: Steroid-sparing\n\n## Prognosis Recall\n- Acute: 50% resolve within 24 hours\n- Chronic idiopathic: 50% resolve within 1 year\n- Physical: Often lifelong, manageable\n\n## Common Exam Mistakes\n- Confusing urticaria with angioedema (different tissues)\n- Thinking all chronic urticaria is allergic (50% idiopathic)\n- Using only antihistamines for serum sickness (needs steroids)\n- Not considering autoimmune subtype (35-40%)\n- Overlooking drug as cause in recent-onset urticaria",
