        summary: "Self-assessment through recall questions on classification, pathophysiology, diagnosis, and management of urticaria.",
        contentMd: "# Active Recall: Urticaria & Drug Reactions\n\n## Level 1: Factual Recall\n\nQ1: Define urticaria.\nA1: Transient edematous reaction manifesting as wheals with intense pruritus, individual lesions lasting <24 hours\n\nQ2: What percentage of chronic idiopathic urticaria is autoimmune?\nA2: 35-40%\n\nQ3: What is the timeline for Type I drug reaction?\nA3: Minutes to 2 hours\n\nQ4: What is the timeline for Type III drug reaction?\nA4: 7-14 days after exposure\n\nQ5: List the seven types of physical urticaria.\nA5: Dermographism, cholinergic, cold, delayed pressure, heat, solar, aquagenic\n\n## Level 2: Conceptual Understanding\n\nQ6: How does IgE-mediated urticaria develop?\nA6: Allergen binding to IgE molecules on mast cell FcεRI receptors causes cross-linking, receptor aggregation, calcium influx, and degranulation\n\nQ7: Explain the wheal formation process.\nA7: Mast cell degranulation releases histamine, which binds H1 receptors on endothelium, increasing vascular permeability, leading to plasma extravasation and dermal edema\n\nQ8: Why is dermographism the most common physical urticaria?\nA8: Mechanical trauma is ubiquitous; mast cells in skin respond to any form of pressure or rubbing\n\nQ9: How does basophil activation test help in chronic urticaria?\nA9: BAT identifies patients with autoimmune urticaria (autoantibodies against IgE/FcεRI) who may benefit from specific therapies like omalizumab\n\nQ10: Why is cold urticaria considered a medical emergency?\nA10: Because large cold exposure (cold water immersion) can cause systemic mast cell activation and anaphylaxis\n\n## Level 3: Application and Clinical Reasoning\n\nQ11: A 20-year-old patient presents with sudden onset urticaria 30 minutes after eating shellfish. Diagnosis and management?\nA11: Type I hypersensitivity to shellfish; management: avoid shellfish, antihistamine (cetirizine 10 mg), epinephrine if anaphylaxis, consider allergy testing for cross-reactivity\n\nQ12: A patient with 3-month history of daily urticaria, unresponsive to cetirizine 10 mg OD. What is the next step?\nA12: Chronic urticaria; investigate for autoimmune (ASST, BAT, thyroid antibodies); increase antihistamine to 20-40 mg or add omalizumab if IgE elevated\n\nQ13: A patient develops urticaria, arthralgia, fever, and lymphadenopathy 10 days after starting antibiotic. Diagnosis?\nA13: Type III reaction (serum sickness); management: discontinue antibiotic, systemic corticosteroids (1-2 weeks), NSAIDs for arthralgia, antihistamines for urticaria\n\nQ14: Explain physical urticaria in a patient with strong dermographic response.\nA14: Dermographism indicates mast cells hyper-responsive to mechanical trauma; risk of symptomatic dermographism with any scratching; management: antihistamines, avoid trauma, reassure about benign course\n\nQ15: Design investigation protocol for new-onset chronic urticaria.\nA15: CBC (eosinophilia, infection), ESR (systemic disease), TSH/TPO (thyroid), LFTs, H. pylori serology, specific IgE (foods), ASST (autoimmune), BAT (autoimmune), parasites if indicated, urinalysis\n\n## Level 4: Differential Diagnosis and Analysis\n\nQ16: Differentiate acute urticaria from erythema multiforme (EM).\nA16: Acute urticaria: <24 hours per lesion, migratory, pruritic; EM: >24-48 hours per lesion, fixed, painful, target lesions\n\nQ17: Compare Type I and Type III drug reactions.\nA17: Type I: Minutes to 2 hours, IgE-mediated, anaphylaxis risk; Type III: 7-14 days, immune complexes, serum sickness with systemic features\n\nQ18: Explain why omalizumab works in some but not all chronic urticaria cases.\nA18: Omalizumab effective when IgE elevated or IgE-mediated autoimmunity; ineffective in non-IgE-mediated autoimmune urticaria or drug-inducible types\n\n## Level 5: Integration and Synthesis\n\nQ19: Design comprehensive management for 35-year-old female with 8-month chronic urticaria, negative allergy workup, positive BAT.\nA19: Diagnosis: Autoimmune urticaria; Step 1: Increase antihistamine to 40 mg cetirizine daily; Step 2: Add omalizumab (blocks IgE); Step 3 if refractory: Cyclosporine; Monitor: Symptom diary, quality of life assessment; Counseling: Chronic course likely, patience with treatment escalation needed\n\nQ20: A patient with cholinergic urticaria asks about exercise restrictions. Counsel appropriately.\nA20: Exercise safe but may trigger symptoms; advise: warm up slowly, exercise in cool environment, avoid hot showers immediately after, take antihistamine 30 min before, wear loose clothing, gradually increase activity tolerance through acclimatization\n\n## Quick Pattern Drills\n\nQ: Most common drug causing immediate urticaria?\nA: Penicillins and cephalosporins\n\nQ: Gold standard test for allergy urticaria?\nA: Prick test for allergen-specific IgE\n\nQ: What makes dermographism positive?\nA: Wheal appearing within 3-5 minutes of firm skin stroking\n\nQ: Treatment for anaphylaxis from urticaria?\nA: Epinephrine 0.3-0.5 mg subcutaneous (1:1000)\n\nQ: Why are second-generation antihistamines preferred?\nA: Non-sedating, allowing daytime function\n\nQ: Percentage resolving acute urticaria within 24 hours?\nA: 50%",
