        title: "Pemphigus & Bullous Pemphigoid - Foundation",
        estimatedMinutes: 20,
        summary: "Overview of autoimmune blistering diseases, pemphigus vs pemphigoid classification, and clinical presentation patterns.",
        contentMd: "# Pemphigus and Bullous Pemphigoid\n\n## Autoimmune Blistering Diseases Classification\n\n### Intraepidermal Blistering\n- Pemphigus group: Autoantibodies to cell surface antigens\n- Mechanism: Acantholysis (loss of intercellular adhesion)\n\n### Subepidermal Blistering\n- Pemphigoid group: Autoantibodies to basement membrane zone\n- Mechanism: Separation at dermal-epidermal junction\n\n## Pemphigus: Overview\n\n### Definition\nAutoimmune disorder with intraepidermal acantholysis causing flaccid blisters.\n\n### Types (IgG Autoantibodies to Desmosomes)\n1. Pemphigus vulgaris: 60-80% of all pemphigus\n2. Pemphigus foliaceus: 20-40%\n3. Paraneoplastic pemphigus: Rare, malignancy-associated\n4. IgA-mediated pemphigus: Very rare\n\n### Pemphigus Vulgaris\n- Autoantigen: Desmoglein 3 (mucosal)\n- Additional: Desmoglein 1 (cutaneous) in severe cases\n- Clinical: Oral involvement common (90%), skin involvement variable\n\n### Pemphigus Foliaceus\n- Autoantigen: Desmoglein 1 only\n- Clinical: Superficial blisters, no oral involvement\n- Variant: Pemphigus vegetans (erosive variant)\n\n## Bullous Pemphigoid: Overview\n\n### Definition\nAutoimmune disorder with subepidermal blister formation.\n\n### Autoantigen\n- BP180 (collagen XVII, transmembrane) - most common\n- BP230 (intracellular component) - less common\n- IgG and IgA autoantibodies\n\n### Clinical Features\n- Tense bullae (don't rupture easily)\n- Urticarial or eczematous pre-bullous lesions\n- Predilection: Flexural and intertriginous areas\n- Mucosal involvement: Rare (unlike pemphigus)\n- Typical age: >60 years (older adults)\n\n## Clinical Comparison\n\n### Pemphigus\n- Bulla: Flaccid, rupture easily\n- Erosions: Painful, slow to heal\n- Mucosa: Often involved (90% in vulgaris)\n- Onset: Any age\n- IgG: Against desmoglein (cell surface)\n\n### Bullous Pemphigoid\n- Bulla: Tense, firm, don't rupture easily\n- Erosions: Less common, heal faster\n- Mucosa: Rarely involved\n- Onset: >60 years typically\n- IgG: Against basement membrane (BP180, BP230)\n\n## Epidemiology\n\n### Pemphigus\n- Incidence: 0.5-5 per million annually\n- Higher in Mediterranean, Jewish, Indian populations\n- More common in middle-aged to older adults (40-60 years)\n\n### Bullous Pemphigoid\n- Incidence: 0.5-2 per million annually\n- Predominantly affects elderly (>60 years)\n- Rare in children\n\n## Risk Factors and Triggers\n\n### Pemphigus\n1. Genetic predisposition (HLA-DRB1, DQB1)\n2. Environmental triggers: Infections, drugs\n3. Drug-induced: ACE inhibitors, penicillamine\n4. Malignancy: Paraneoplastic pemphigus\n\n### Bullous Pemphigoid\n1. Age (elderly)\n2. Medications: NSAIDs, diuretics (can trigger)\n3. Dermatitis herpetiformis\n4. Psoriasis\n5. Autoimmune thyroid disease",
