        layer: 2,
        slug: "pemphigus-mechanism",
        title: "Pemphigus & Bullous Pemphigoid - Mechanism",
        estimatedMinutes: 25,
        summary: "Detailed pathophysiology of acantholysis, autoimmune mechanisms, antibody role in blistering, and molecular mechanisms.",
        contentMd: "# Pathophysiology of Pemphigus and Bullous Pemphigoid\n\n## Pemphigus: Acantholysis Mechanism\n\n### Desmosome Structure\n1. Desmosomes: Cell-cell adhesion junctions\n2. Desmogleins: Cadherin-family transmembrane proteins\n3. Desmoplakin: Intracellular anchoring proteins\n\n### Desmoglein Types\n1. Desmoglein 1 (Dsg1): Superficial epidermis\n2. Desmoglein 3 (Dsg3): Basal and suprabasal layers, oral mucosa\n\n### Antibody-Mediated Acantholysis\n\n#### Pemphigus Vulgaris\n1. IgG autoantibodies to Dsg3 (and Dsg1)\n2. Antibody binding to desmoglein\n3. Disruption of adhesion complex\n4. Loss of cell-cell contact (acantholysis)\n5. Suprabasal blister formation\n\n#### Pemphigus Foliaceus\n1. IgG autoantibodies to Dsg1 only\n2. Superficial (subcorneal) blister formation\n3. No mucosal involvement (Dsg1 not prominent in mucosa)\n\n### Molecular Mechanisms\n\n1. Direct effect: Antibody binding blocks adhesion\n2. Complement activation: C3 deposition enhances pathology\n3. Apoptosis: Keratinocyte apoptosis from signal disruption\n4. Cytokine release: TNF-α, IL-6 amplify inflammation\n\n### Histopathology of Pemphigus\n1. Acantholysis: Loss of intercellular adhesion\n2. Intraepidermal blister: Fluid collection between cells\n3. Suprabasal blister: Basal cells remain attached\n4. Minimal inflammation in early lesions\n5. Tzanck cells: Rounded keratinocytes in blister fluid\n\n## Bullous Pemphigoid: Basement Membrane Disruption\n\n### BP180 and BP230\n1. BP180 (Collagen XVII): Transmembrane protein, hemidesmosomal\n2. BP230: Intracellular anchoring protein\n3. Autoantigen: Extracellular NC16A domain of BP180\n\n### Pathogenic Mechanism\n\n1. IgG and IgA autoantibodies to BP180/BP230\n2. Antibody binding recruits complement\n3. Complement activation: C3, C5a\n4. Mast cell recruitment and degranulation\n5. Neutrophil infiltration\n6. Serine protease release\n7. Enzymatic degradation of anchoring filaments\n8. Blister formation at dermal-epidermal junction\n\n### Role of Complement\n1. C3 and C5a activation\n2. Mast cell chemotaxis\n3. Neutrophil recruitment\n4. Mast cell degranulation: Tryptase and chymase\n5. Protease activity: Collagen degradation\n\n### Histopathology of Bullous Pemphigoid\n1. Subepidermal blister: Below intact epidermis\n2. Dense inflammatory infiltrate: Neutrophils and eosinophils\n3. Eosinophil microabscesses at blister base\n4. Linear IgG and C3 at basement membrane zone\n5. Blister roof: Epidermal cells intact\n\n## Immunopathology\n\n### Direct Immunofluorescence (DIF)\n\n#### Pemphigus Vulgaris\n- IgG and C3: Intracellular (cell surface)\n- Pattern: \"Chicken wire\" or tombstone appearance\n\n#### Bullous Pemphigoid\n- IgG and C3: Linear at basement membrane zone\n- Pattern: Continuous linear along BMZ\n\n### Indirect Immunofluorescence (IIF)\n- Pemphigus: IgG in serum (antibody titer correlates with disease severity)\n- Bullous pemphigoid: IgG/IgA in serum (less common than pemphigus)\n\n### Serology\n1. ELISA for desmoglein-specific IgG\n   - Anti-Dsg3: Pemphigus vulgaris and foliaceus\n   - Anti-Dsg1: Pemphigus foliaceus and severe vulgaris\n\n2. ELISA for BP antigens\n   - Anti-BP180: Most specific for BP\n   - Anti-BP230: Less sensitive\n\n## Trigger Mechanisms\n\n### Pemphigus Triggers\n1. Infections: Streptococcal, staphylococcal\n2. Drugs: ACE inhibitors, penicillamine, NSAIDs\n3. Ultraviolet exposure\n4. Malignancy: Paraneoplastic pemphigus\n5. Autoimmune thyroiditis\n\n### Bullous Pemphigoid Triggers\n1. NSAIDs and aspirin\n2. Diuretics\n3. Beta-blockers\n4. Dermatitis and trauma\n5. Vaccination\n6. UV exposure\n\n## Genetic Factors\n\n### HLA Associations\n- Pemphigus vulgaris: HLA-DR4, HLA-DQ2\n- Pemphigus foliaceus: HLA-DR3\n- Bullous pemphigoid: HLA-DR3 (less strong)\n\n### Inheritance\n- Not strongly heritable\n- Genetic predisposition in some families\n- Environmental triggers essential for disease development",
