        slug: "pemphigus-exam-prep",
        title: "Pemphigus & Bullous Pemphigoid - Exam Preparation",
        estimatedMinutes: 20,
        summary: "Key examination points: diagnostic criteria, immunology, investigations, and management algorithms.",
        contentMd: "# Pemphigus & Bullous Pemphigoid: Examination Focus\n\n## Classification Summary\n\n### Pemphigus (Intraepidermal)\n1. Vulgaris: Dsg3 + Dsg1, oral involvement common\n2. Foliaceus: Dsg1 only, superficial, no oral\n3. Paraneoplastic: Associated with malignancy\n\n### Bullous Pemphigoid (Subepidermal)\n1. BP180 (collagen XVII): Most common\n2. BP230: Less common\n3. Age: Predominantly >60 years\n\n## Desmosome Components\n- Desmoglein 1: Superficial epidermis\n- Desmoglein 3: Basal and suprabasal layers, oral mucosa\n- Desmoplakin: Intracellular anchoring\n\n## Key Differentiating Features\n\n### Bullae Characteristics\n- Pemphigus: Flaccid, rupture easily\n- Bullous pemphigoid: Tense, firm, intact\n\n### Oral Involvement\n- Pemphigus vulgaris: 90% (painful erosions)\n- Pemphigus foliaceus: 0% (superficial)\n- Bullous pemphigoid: Rare (<10%)\n\n### Age of Onset\n- Pemphigus: Any age (40-60 common)\n- Bullous pemphigoid: Elderly (>60 typical)\n\n### Histopathology Location\n- Pemphigus: Intraepidermal (suprabasal or subcorneal)\n- Bullous pemphigoid: Subepidermal\n\n## Immunopathology Findings\n\n### Direct Immunofluorescence\n- Pemphigus: IgG intercellular (cell surface)\n- Bullous pemphigoid: IgG linear at BMZ\n- Both may have C3 deposition\n\n### Indirect Immunofluorescence\n- Pemphigus: Often positive (antibody in serum)\n- Bullous pemphigoid: Less often positive\n\n### ELISA Antigens\n- Anti-Dsg3: Pemphigus vulgaris\n- Anti-Dsg1: Pemphigus foliaceus, severe vulgaris\n- Anti-BP180: Bullous pemphigoid (most specific)\n- Anti-BP230: Bullous pemphigoid (less sensitive)\n\n## Diagnostic Algorithm\n\n### Clinical Suspicion → Histopathology → DIF → ELISA\n\n1. Histopathology\n   - Pemphigus: Intraepidermal acantholysis\n   - Bullous pemphigoid: Subepidermal blister, eosinophils\n\n2. DIF\n   - Confirms acantholysis (pemphigus) or BMZ pathology (BP)\n   - Shows pattern and location\n\n3. ELISA\n   - Specific antigen identification\n   - Quantitative for disease monitoring\n\n## Treatment Principles\n\n### Pemphigus Management\n\nPhase 1: Induction\n- Prednisolone 1-1.5 mg/kg/day\n- Azathioprine 1-2 mg/kg/day added\n\nPhase 2: Consolidation\n- Gradual steroid taper\n- Continue azathioprine\n\nPhase 3: Maintenance\n- Lowest effective steroid dose\n- Azathioprine continuation\n\n### Bullous Pemphigoid Management\n\nMild: Topical Corticosteroids\n- Clobetasol propionate 0.05%\n- Can achieve remission\n\nModerate-Severe: Systemic Therapy\n- Prednisolone 0.5-1 mg/kg/day\n- Azathioprine or mycophenolate\n- Dapsone alternative\n\n## Steroid-Sparing Agents\n1. Azathioprine: 1-2 mg/kg/day (slow, 6-8 weeks)\n2. Mycophenolate mofetil: 1.5-3 g/day (faster)\n3. Dapsone: 50-100 mg/day (requires G6PD test)\n4. Rituximab: For refractory disease\n\n## Tzanck Smear Interpretation\n- Normal keratinocytes: Intact borders, central nucleus\n- Tzanck cells: Rounded, loose borders, hyperchromatic nucleus\n- Specific for acantholysis (pemphigus)\n- Cannot differentiate type of pemphigus\n\n## Disease Monitoring\n\n### Serological\n- ELISA titer: Reflects disease activity\n- Rising titer: Suggests relapse risk\n- Helps guide therapy tapering\n\n### Clinical\n- Number of new lesions\n- Erosion healing rate\n- Medication side effects\n\n## Exam-Pattern Distinguishing Features\n\n### Pemphigus vs Bullous Pemphigoid\n\nFeature | Pemphigus | Bullous Pemphigoid\n- Blister type: Flaccid | Tense\n- Location: Intraepidermal | Subepidermal\n- Oral: 90% | <10%\n- Age: Any | >60\n- Nikolsky sign: Positive | Negative\n- Histology: Acantholysis | Eosinophil abscesses\n- DIF pattern: Intercellular | Linear BMZ\n- Antigen: Desmoglein | BP180/BP230\n\n## Common Exam Questions\n1. Histopathology location (intra vs subepidermal)\n2. Antigen specificity (Dsg vs BP)\n3. DIF pattern interpretation\n4. Management step-up approach\n5. Steroid-sparing agent selection\n6. Disease monitoring parameters\n7. Prognosis and mortality\n\n## Critical Drug Information\n- Prednisolone: Induction 1-1.5 mg/kg, slow taper critical\n- Azathioprine: TPMT testing before use\n- Dapsone: G6PD screening mandatory\n- Rituximab: CD20+ B cell depletion",
