        summary: "Overview of Stevens-Johnson Syndrome and Toxic Epidermal Necrolysis, classification by severity, epidemiology, and clinical presentation.",
        contentMd: "# Stevens-Johnson Syndrome and Toxic Epidermal Necrolysis\n\n## Definitions\n\n### Stevens-Johnson Syndrome (SJS)\nSevere mucocutaneous reaction with <10% body surface area (BSA) involvement.\n\n### Toxic Epidermal Necrolysis (TEN)\nSevere mucocutaneous reaction with >30% BSA involvement.\n\n### SJS/TEN Overlap\n10-30% BSA involvement (intermediate form).\n\n## Classification by BSART (Body Surface Area Affected)\n- SJS: <10% epidermal detachment\n- SJS/TEN overlap: 10-30%\n- TEN: >30% epidermal detachment\n\n## Clinical Features Overview\n\n### Prodromal Phase (1-3 days)\n1. Fever, malaise, myalgia\n2. Headache, cough\n3. Arthralgia (in 30%)\n4. Similar to viral upper respiratory infection\n\n### Exanthem Phase (1-7 days)\n1. Maculopapular rash, often urticarial\n2. Spread from face/trunk to extremities\n3. Painful lesions\n4. Purpura and blistering\n5. Nikolsky sign positive\n\n### Mucosal Involvement\n1. Oral: Erosions, hemorrhagic crusts (90%)\n2. Ocular: Conjunctivitis, severe in TEN (80%)\n3. Genital: Erosions (50%)\n4. Respiratory: Tracheal involvement in severe cases\n5. GI: Esophageal ulceration\n\n## Histopathological Features\n1. Full-thickness epidermal necrosis\n2. Dermal-epidermal separation at basement membrane\n3. Minimal dermal inflammation (paradoxical)\n4. Necrotic keratinocytes\n5. Sparse lymphocytic infiltrate\n\n## Epidemiology\n\n### Incidence\n- SJS: 1-6 per million per year\n- TEN: 0.4-1.3 per million per year\n- Overlap common: 25-50% of cases\n\n### Demographics\n- Age: Bi-modal (1-6 years and 40+ years)\n- Gender: Slightly female predominance\n- Mortality: SJS 1-5%, TEN 30-50%, increasing with age\n\n## Major Causative Agents\n\n### Medications (Most Common - 80%)\n1. Antibiotics: Sulfonamides, beta-lactams, fluoroquinolones\n2. Anticonvulsants: Phenytoin, carbamazepine, phenobarbital\n3. NSAIDs: Ibuprofen, naproxen\n4. Antiretrovirals: Nevirapine, abacavir\n5. Allopurinol (strong association)\n\n### Infections\n1. Viral: HSV-1 (most common), EBV, CMV, HCV\n2. Bacterial: Streptococcal, mycobacterial\n3. Fungal: Histoplasmosis, coccidioidomycosis\n\n### Idiopathic\n- 25-50% of cases (no identifiable cause)\n\n## Risk Factors\n1. Genetic predisposition (HLA-B*58:01 for allopurinol)\n2. Immunosuppression (HIV/AIDS)\n3. Systemic lupus erythematosus\n4. Previous SJS/TEN episode\n5. High-dose medications\n6. Recent infection",
