        contentMd: "# Active Recall: SJS & TEN\n\n## Level 1: Factual Recall\n\nQ1: What percentage BSA defines TEN?\nA1: >30% epidermal detachment\n\nQ2: What is the mortality rate for TEN with appropriate care?\nA2: 30-50%, increases with age and BSA >30%\n\nQ3: What is the most common drug cause of SJS/TEN?\nA3: Sulfonamide antibiotics (TMP-SMX)\n\nQ4: What is the most common infectious cause of SJS/TEN?\nA4: Herpes simplex virus type 1 (HSV-1)\n\nQ5: What percentage of SJS/TEN cases are idiopathic?\nA5: 25-50%\n\n## Level 2: Conceptual Understanding\n\nQ6: Explain the pathophysiology of keratinocyte necrosis in SJS/TEN.\nA6: CD8+ T cells recognize drug-protein hapten complex, activate, infiltrate skin, kill keratinocytes via Fas-FasL interaction and perforin-granzyme pathway causing full-thickness epidermal necrosis\n\nQ7: Why is minimal dermal inflammation paradoxical in SJS/TEN?\nA7: Despite massive epidermal necrosis, dermal infiltrate is sparse, suggesting direct CTL-mediated mechanism rather than inflammatory cascade\n\nQ8: How does HLA genotype influence SJS/TEN risk?\nA8: HLA peptide-binding groove variations affect drug presentation to TCR; HLA-B*58:01 increases allopurinol risk 1000-fold\n\nQ9: What is SCORTEN and why is it important?\nA9: SCORTEN is mortality predictor score using 6 factors; scores ≥5 predict 90% mortality; helps guide intensity of treatment\n\nQ10: Why is early drug discontinuation critical?\nA10: Drug-specific T cells continue attacking keratinocytes; stopping drug removes ongoing stimulus, allows immune system to resolve\n\n## Level 3: Application and Clinical Reasoning\n\nQ11: 55-year-old with fever, target rash, and Nikolsky sign positive for 2 days. Hospitalized with 20% BSA. Management?\nA11: Admit ICU, identify offending drug (recent meds?), start IV fluid resuscitation (3 × kg × 20), ophthalmology consultation, consider IVIG if TEN, supportive care, pain control, monitor SCORTEN\n\nQ12: Patient on allopurinol develops SJS. Genetic testing shows HLA-B*58:01. Explain risk.\nA12: HLA-B*58:01 binds allopurinol metabolite efficiently, presents to TCR with high affinity, 1000-fold increased risk; allopurinol should be avoided in future\n\nQ13: Histopathology shows full-thickness epidermal necrosis with minimal dermal inflammation. Clinical diagnosis?\nA13: SJS or TEN (depending on BSA); minimal inflammation supports drug-induced (CTL-mediated) rather than inflammatory pathology\n\nQ14: Debate: Use of systemic corticosteroids in acute TEN.\nA14: Current evidence: Mixed; early use (48-72 hours) may help, but prolonged use increases infection risk; IVIG preferred; most experts recommend avoiding steroids or using minimally\n\nQ15: Design investigation protocol for suspected SJS.\nA15: Skin biopsy (H&E + DIF if autoimmune question), CBC (eosinophilia, infection signs), CMP (SCORTEN components), LFTs, coagulation studies, urinalysis, blood cultures if fever, ophthalmology evaluation\n\n## Level 4: Differential Diagnosis\n\nQ16: Differentiate SJS from erythema multiforme (EM) based on targets.\nA16: SJS: Atypical flat targets (lack 3 zones), mucosal involvement common, purpura prominent; EM: Classic targets (3 distinct zones), minimal mucosal involvement, on extremities\n\nQ17: Compare drug reaction exanthem with SJS clinically and histologically.\nA17: Exanthem: Milder, small BSA, no Nikolsky, minimal systemic symptoms, sparse perivascular infiltrate; SJS: Severe, large BSA, positive Nikolsky, systemic illness, full-thickness necrosis\n\nQ18: How would you differentiate SJS from toxic shock syndrome (TSS)?\nA18: SJS: Drug history, widespread rash with targets, Nikolsky positive, minimal systemic toxicity initially; TSS: Streptococcal/staphylococcal context, erythematous rash without targets, profound shock\n\n## Level 5: Integration and Synthesis\n\nQ19: Design comprehensive management for 38-year-old with TEN (35% BSA) presenting day 3 of illness.\nA19: Immediate: Admit to ICU/burn unit, identify drug (? antibiotic), discontinue immediately, establish large-bore IV × 2; Resuscitation: 3 × 38 × 35 = 3990 mL over 24 hrs, adjust for urine output; Ophthalmology: Urgent evaluation; IVIG: 2 g/kg (76 g) over 3-5 days; Wound care: Sterile technique, daily baths, non-adherent dressings; Pain: IV opioids; Nutrition: High protein; Monitor: SCORTEN, CBC, CMP, infection; Avoid: Long-term steroids; Support: Psychological, sedation if needed\n\nQ20: A physician was prescribing allopurinol to a patient with HLA-B*58:01 status unknown. Discuss prevention and counseling.\nA20: Prevention: Genetic testing should be done before allopurinol use in high-risk populations (Asian); Counseling: Explain 1000-fold increased risk with HLA-B*58:01, discuss alternative xanthine oxidase inhibitors (febuxostat); if allopurinol necessary, low-dose initiation with slow titration; Warn: Report fever, rash, oral ulcers immediately; Document: HLA status in medical record\n\n## Quick Pattern Drills\n\nQ: What distinguishes flat atypical targets of SJS from true targets of EM?\nA: True targets have 3 zones (pale center, red middle, purple border); atypical have only 1-2 zones\n\nQ: SCORTEN score of 5 predicts what mortality rate?\nA: >90% mortality\n\nQ: What is the fluid requirement for TEN using modified Parkland?\nA: 3 × kg × %BSA, not standard 4 × kg × %BSA\n\nQ: Which drug has strongest HLA association?\nA: Allopurinol with HLA-B*58:01 (1000-fold risk)\n\nQ: What is the pathological hallmark of SJS/TEN?\nA: Full-thickness epidermal necrosis with minimal dermal inflammation\n\nQ: When is IVIG administered in TEN?\nA: Early in disease course (first 3-5 days), before extensive damage",
